history.text: Hi. Have you seen this movie? What did you think of it?
Yes, I've seen the movie. I thought that it was better than all the other recent DC movies, but to be honest, I don't know if it deserved a 92% rating on Rotten Tomatoes. What about you?

I did like it better than the other DC movies. Not as Dark and dismal as they always are. It also had a bit more humor, which was refreshing, but i think that was the casting of Pine more than anything

I hone
stly have never understood rotten tomatoes percentages, half the time i agree, half the time i don't
personally i still prefer Marvel to DC

I agree. Rotten Tomatoes definitely seems to be biased towards certain movies from what I see. And yes, Marvel is WAY better. But back to Wonder Woman, what did you think of Gal Gadot's portrayal of Wonder Woman?
It was definitely a stretch from Linda Carter... but if i separate the show from the movie, I liked her.
nice to see strength and curves for once and not just sex
Yeah totally. I was afraid that it was going to be all just sexy shots of Wonder Woman who happens to also fight, but they did a pretty good job of making it not about sexiness at all.
I don't know why previous movies with female superheroes couldn't do this way beforehand.
I have to admit,I liked the twist at the end of who the villain really was. I totally missed that.
Casting there was really good too.  He was not your typical Strong type of villain either.
Haha yeah .I didn't like the villain too much though. He was too underplayed.
I didn't really read the comics, but was Wonder Woman always the daughter of Zeus? Or was that unique only to the film universe?
the notes say that she is the half sibling of Ares and daughter of Hippolyta and Zues.. i do not remember that being in the tv show, but i did not read the comics either.
I only remember she was an Amazonian.
Yeah that's what I thought too. I guess it doesn't really matter about her origins too much
but what I didn't like was how Ares still held onto his British appearance and accent even after revealing himself to be Ares. That really took me out of the movie.
With a lot of these genres, i find it is easier to separate film from comic and TV. there are too many differences to know what is conon sometimes.
That's true.
I kind of liked it... making it how even a God could be an everyman.   but i see your point.  he was almost "too" normal when fighting her.
Another thing that I didn't understand was why they initially refused to train Diana when everyone knew that she was the daughter of Zeus and literally the only person on earth who could stop Ares.
On an island full of fierce warrior culture, why would they not want to utilize the best weapon they have against their fight to keep earth safe?

i was frustrated with Hippolyta's refusal for Antiope to train her/... i mean, you are a warrior race of badass women. teach the daughter of zeus to protect herself because you KNOW something is goig to happen some day. it just HAS to. it always does. lol

and my typing just went haywire. sorry about
 that
Haha no worries. And yeah seriously!
especially when on a "hidden" island with only fog to really hid you?
like someone, some day isn't going to go in there... and does.

You know another thing I kind of didn't understand? On an island full of women, did they just start out with a set number that kept dwindling down as amazon warriors died off? Or was there some way that they were able to keep their population growing or at least stable?
i think they age more slowly..... if they don't all have gods blood in them they have something
demigods maybe?

Hah makes sense. So if Ares main goal is to cause the destruction of human life, why doesn't he just use his powers to kill everyone himself? Seems like no modern technology at that time posed a threat to him.
never really thought about it.
Ares could single handedly wipe out everyone by himself if he wanted.
because ares is the god of war. but he does not start it himself
he manipulates man to start it amongst themselves
kind of like loki is trickery and manipulates .. ares seems much the same way.

the sheet says "although he has
subtly given humans ideas and inspirations, using Ludendorff and Maru as pawns in the
process, it is ultimately their decision to resort to violence as they are inherently corrupt."
Just seems really inefficient considering the abilities that Ares already has haha
i agree. but every depiction i have ever seen of ares is the same way... even in Xena.. lol
That's true. Oh man Xena brings back memories.
I would much rather see a Xena movie than a DC movie LOL
i would totally watch Xena if it was on Netflix
before any DC movie
Heck yeah! Wait, was Xena also a Amazon princess of some kind or was she just a warrior princess?
I forget... been so long....
just Warrior Princess... there was episode where it was thought that Ares was her father, but it was never proven
Xena and Hercules. now that brings me back to my teenage years.
so much better than the current batman and superman combined

wonder woman could fit in with
 them though.

True that! By the way, didn't Steve's decision to sacrifice himself by flying that plane at the end of Wonder Woman totally remind you of Steve's decision to sacrifice himself by flying that plane at the end of Captain America?
she had the body and accent. lol
Yeah I agree.

Chris Pine... Chris Evans.... lets throw Chris Pratt into it too and Star Lords decision to sacrifice himself by throwing himself into space to save Gamora....
it's all the same hero gimmick.
Seriously... these writers have got to come up with some original ideas for a change....
Yes!

 the top
